These first few nat lemmas that aren't specific to the GodelBetaFunction should be moved to earlier files in the library.
I have moved them to Mathlib.Data.Zmod.Coprime
We already have [List.encodable](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Logic/Equiv/List.html#List.encodable). How is this different from `encode`/`decode` for lists?
Or perhaps even more closely related: [Equiv.listNatEquivNat](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Logic/Equiv/List.html#Equiv.listNatEquivNat)

Goedel's beta function is used to prove that arithmetically definable functions are equal to `Partrec'` ([the desired lemma](https://github.com/iehality/lean4-logic/blob/7a12751321928ed48c565b6db906d1d8a303ed25/Logic/Vorspiel/Arith.lean#L500)). While `List.encodable` is computable, it is not immediately apparent whether it is arithmetically definable.

But it is arithmetically definable. `encodeList` and `decodeList` are defined in terms of `Nat.pair` and `Nat.unpair`, and these are arithmetically definable (I guess it might be hardest to prove that for `Nat.sqrt`). 
I think it would be nicer to prove this reusing existing Mathlib definitions.

The term arithmetically definable function, we mean here a class of functions whose graph can be described by a $\Sigma_1$ formula of arithmetic.  While it is straightforward to prove that this class is closed under function composition, but whether it is closed in primitive recursion is a proposition demanding a technical proof (we use beta function lemma to prove this). Since `encodeList` and `decodeList` are defined using recursion, they cannot be used to prove this.

I see. Thanks for the explanation. 
In that case, we will probably want both. Can you reference the relation to `encodeList`/`decodeList` and why we also need this version in docstrings and/or the module doc?
OK I have added that to the documentation. Thanks Floris.

```suggestion
This file proves GÃ¶del's Beta Function Lemma, used to prove the First Incompleteness Theorem. It
permits  quantification over finite sequences of natural numbers in formal theories of arithmetic.
This Beta Function has no connection with the unrelated Beta Function defined in analysis. Note
that `Nat.beta` and `Nat.unbeta` provide similar functionality to `Encodable.encodeList` and 
`Encodable.decodeList`. We define these separately, because it is easier to prove that `Nat.beta` 
and `Nat.unbeta` are arithmetically definable, and this is hard to prove that for 
`Encodable.encodeList` and `Encodable.decodeList` directly. The arithmetic
definability is needed for the proof of the First Incompleteness Theorem.
```
